WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.324
A ladybug lands on the 12 of a clock, 

00:00:02.324 --> 00:00:04.710
and every second she moves randomly to 

00:00:04.710 --> 00:00:07.034
a neighboring number, either one step 

00:00:07.034 --> 00:00:09.420
clockwise or one step counterclockwise.

00:00:09.740 --> 00:00:12.158
Here each time she touches a number I'm 

00:00:12.158 --> 00:00:14.637
colouring it red, and on this run of the 

00:00:14.637 --> 00:00:17.600
simulation, the last number to get coloured is 3.

00:00:18.660 --> 00:00:20.838
And if I run the simulation a second time, 

00:00:20.838 --> 00:00:23.118
again where she continues until every number 

00:00:23.118 --> 00:00:25.500
is coloured, the last one to get coloured is 1.

00:00:26.720 --> 00:00:29.928
My puzzle for you is what is the probability that 

00:00:29.928 --> 00:00:32.880
the very last number to get coloured is the 6?

00:00:34.120 --> 00:00:36.005
This is the first in a set of monthly puzzles 

00:00:36.005 --> 00:00:37.809
that I'll be posting this year as part of a 

00:00:37.809 --> 00:00:39.572
collaboration with the mathematician Peter 

00:00:39.572 --> 00:00:39.900
Winkler.

00:00:40.460 --> 00:00:41.993
The spirit of it is to not give away 

00:00:41.993 --> 00:00:43.486
the answer right away, we both want 

00:00:43.486 --> 00:00:45.020
to give you a chance to mull it over.

00:00:45.540 --> 00:00:47.982
Every month Peter is going to hop onto a Zoom 

00:00:47.982 --> 00:00:50.636
call to talk through a very elegant way to answer 

00:00:50.636 --> 00:00:53.185
the relevant puzzle, and if you want to sign up 

00:00:53.185 --> 00:00:55.840
to join those, go to momath.org slash mindbenders.

00:00:55.900 --> 00:00:58.320
It's all part of the MoMath Museum's Year of Math.

